  <li id='source-widget-4' class='source-item'>
    <div class='source_header'>
      <strong class='source_title'>Biomass Carbon Stocks in the year 2000</strong>
    </div>

    <div class='source_body'>
      <div class='source_summary'>
        <p>Average biomass carbon density values, as estimated from forest inventories and/or spatially-explicit mapping products, are used to estimate total biomass carbon stocks within an area of interest by multiplying density values by the forest area under consideration at the relevant scale of analysis (national, subnational, or within specific areas of interest).</p>
        <h3>WHRC/WRI</h3>
        <p>The biomass density maps on GFW Climate were produced at 30 x 30 m spatial resolution and are representative of the year 2000. Values for each pixel refer to the average woody biomass of forests within the pixel, and can be used directly to estimate the total biomass carbon stock within the pixel. Pixels are then aggregated to estimate total biomass carbon stocks at the relevant scale of analysis (national, subnational, or within specific areas of interest). On GFW Climate, a user can adjust the minimum tree canopy density threshold for what defines a forest at a value between 10% and 30%, and biomass carbon stock estimates will update accordingly to reflect the new forest definition.</p>
        <h3>FAO</h3>
        <p>Estimates of above- and belowground biomass carbon stocks in the year 2000 are based on FAO’s Forest Resource Assessment 2015, which compiles country-level data that are self-reported by countries every five years using their own inventories, surveys and maps. Source data on biomass estimates from FAO country reports are summarized (here).</p>

        <p class='credits'><strong>Citations:</strong> Zarin, D., Harris, N.L., et al. 2015. Can carbon emissions from tropical deforestation drop by 50% in five years? Global Change Biology, in press.</p>
        <p class="credits">FAO-FRA, “Global Forest Resources Assessment 2015” <a href="http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4793e.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4793e.pdf</a></p>

