  <li id='source-widget-5' class='source-item'>
    <div class='source_header'>
      <strong class='source_title'>Biomass Carbon Density in the year 2000</strong>
    </div>

    <div class='source_body'>
      <div class='source_summary'>
        <p>Biomass carbon density represents the average carbon content of all living plant biomass per unit land area, both above the soil - including stem, stump, branches, bark, seeds and foliage - and below the soil in live roots. A number of different methodological approaches yield estimates of biomass carbon density. At the most fundamental level, all of these rely on the collection of reliable data within inventory plots on the ground, where typically the diameter at breast height (DBH) of individual trees are measured by field technicians and converted to tree biomass estimates using allometric equations. Due to methodological difficulties associated with measuring root biomass, applying a default root : shoot ratio is a core method for estimating belowground (root) biomass from the more easily measured aboveground biomass. Biomass of the forest understory is generally excluded from the aboveground biomass estimates in broadscale carbon accounting</p>
        <h3>WHRC</h3>
        <p>Estimates are derived from a 30 m resolution map of aboveground woody biomass density across the tropics, developed by Woods Hole Research Center using a combination of ground measurements, GLAS LiDAR waveform metrics and Landsat 7 ETM+ satellite imagery and products, elevation and other biophysical variables. Belowground biomass is calculated from aboveground biomass using equation from Mokany et al. On GFW Climate, a user can adjust the minimum tree canopy density threshold for what defines a forest at a value between 10% and 30%, and biomass carbon density estimates will update accordingly to reflect the new forest definition.</p>
        <h3>FAO</h3>
        <p>Estimates of above- and belowground biomass carbon density in the year 2000 are based on FAO’s Forest Resource Assessment 2015, which compiles country-level data that are self-reported by countries every five years using their own inventories, surveys and maps. Source data on biomass estimates from FAO country reports are summarized (here).</p>

        <p class='credits'><strong>Citations:</strong> Zarin, D., Harris, N.L., et al. 2015. Can carbon emissions from tropical deforestation drop by 50% in five years? Global Change Biology, in press.</p>
        <p class="credits">FAO-FRA, “Global Forest Resources Assessment 2015” <a href="http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4793e.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4793e.pdf</a></p>

      </div>
